					<h4>Chick Magnet</h4>
		
		<h1>Elizabeth Gilbert Packs the Boulder Book Store</h1>
		<h2><i></i></h2>
		<div class="text-feature_print">
							<p>By Jenny Shank, 2-13-07</p>
			
							<table width="25" align="right" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0">
					<tr>
						<td>&nbsp;</td>
						<td><img src="http://www.newwest.net/images/thumbnails_feature/eatpraylove_thumb.jpg" style="float: right; margin: 3px;" border="0" alt="" width="100" height="150" /></td>
					</tr>
					<tr><td><img src="http://www.newwest.net/images/spacer.gif" width="1" height="3" border="0" /></td></tr>

					
					<tr><td><img src="http://www.newwest.net/images/spacer.gif" width="1" height="3" border="0" /></td></tr>
				</table>
			
							<p><a target="_blank" href="http://www.elizabethgilbert.com/" title="Elizabeth Gilbert">Elizabeth Gilbert</a> visited the <a target="_blank" href="http://www.boulderbookstore.com" title="Boulder Book Store">Boulder Book Store</a> Monday night to promote the paperback edition of her spiritual travel memoir, <i>Eat Pray Love: One Woman&#8217;s Search for Everything Across Italy, India and Indonesia</i>, and from the looks of the crowd jamming the aisles, virtually every woman in Boulder between the ages of 25 and 70 showed up.&nbsp; It was the largest crowd I&#8217;ve ever seen at the bookstore, probably due to the Boulder-friendly subject matter of Gilbert&#8217;s popular book.&nbsp; &#8220;I was walking through downtown Boulder today,&#8221; she said, &#8220;and I thought, this is the one town where I won&#8217;t get the question, &#8216;Is it selfish to go on a spiritual journey?&#8217;&#8221;  She added, &#8220;They really grill you about that in St. Paul.&#8221;
</p>
<p>
Instead of reading from the book, Gilbert discussed the ideas behind it and took questions from the audience.&nbsp; In the book, Gilbert writes about how she recovered from the depression induced by the breakup of her marriage by traveling.&nbsp; She ate her way across Italy, spent four months meditating in an ashram in India, and then went to work with a traditional healer in Indonesia.&nbsp; She said that many people have asked her if it&#8217;s possible to go on a spiritual journey if they are not at liberty to travel around the world for a year.&nbsp; Gilbert said, &#8220;It&#8217;s not necessary that you travel, but it&#8217;s vital that you shift.&#8221;  
</p>
<p>
She described a sign she once saw at a rec center in Knoxville, Tennessee: &#8220;Warning: Any motion whatsoever brings the possibility of injury.&#8221;  She said that this is true in a metaphoric sense as well, and &#8220;it&#8217;s why people don&#8217;t move.&#8221;  Gilbert said that her book was written in the tradition of quest narratives, and that traditionally there haven&#8217;t been many stories of &#8220;girl journeyers.&#8221;  
</p>
<p>
An audience member asked what it was like for her to return to the U.S. after a year of international travel.&nbsp; &#8220;I was excited to come back and try out my new self.&#8221;  But when she returned to New York, which she had &#8220;always thought of as a cozy little village,&#8221; she decided the city was not for her.&nbsp; One Manhattan man she saw epitomized the New York experience for her: &#8220;I saw a guy striding down the street, eating a bagel while talking on a cell phone, walking his dog and reading the paper.&nbsp; He was just cramming the bagel into his mouth to try to get the nourishment out of the way.&nbsp; It&#8217;s not that I think you should sit down and have a six-course Italian meal every day, but you know, chew the bagel.&#8221;
</p>
<p>
Gilbert said that she wrote the book using journals she had kept during her travels while on a six-week residency at an artists&#8217; retreat in Wyoming.&nbsp; She&#8217;d previously spent time in Wyoming after she graduated from college and &#8220;decided that I was going to be a cowgirl.&#8221;
</p>
<p>
Many audience members wanted to hear updates about the people in the book.&nbsp; Gilbert said that she and Felipe, the Brazilian man she met in Bali, are getting married in two weeks.&nbsp; &#8220;For people who have triple continent lives, we made the only sane decision.&nbsp; We bought a house in Jersey.&#8221;  Gilbert confirmed that Julia Roberts has purchased the film rights to the book, but said she didn&#8217;t know if the movie would ever be made, and that she&#8217;ll have no involvement in the screenplay.&nbsp; Gilbert says for her next project, she&#8217;s writing a book about marriage.
<br />

</p>
						<b>[End of article]</b>
		</div>

